      "message": "Extra here: Could we actually test the cache?\n```\n\nconst char* httpDateRegex \u003d\n    \"(Mon|Tue|Wed|Thu|Fri|Sat|Sun), \"\n    \"(0[1-9]|[12][0-9]|3[01]) \"\n    \"(Jan|Feb|Mar|Apr|May|Jun|Jul|Aug|Sep|Oct|Nov|Dec) \"\n    \"[0-9]{4} \"\n    \"([01][0-9]|2[0-3]):[0-5][0-9]:[0-5][0-9] GMT\";\n\n// Call the cache twice in a row, returns the same\n    const std::string firstCacheDate \u003d server.getCachedDateStr();\n    const std::string secondCacheDate \u003d server.getCachedDateStr();\n\n\n    EXPECT_THAT(firstCacheDate, MatchesRegex(httpDateRegex));\n    EXPECT_THAT(secondCacheDate, MatchesRegex(httpDateRegex));\n    EXPECT_EQ(firstCacheDate, secondCacheDate);\n```\nTwo calls in a row..? \n```\n    const std::string firstCacheDate \u003d server.getCachedDateStr();\n\n    std::this_thread::sleep_for(std::chrono::seconds(11));\n\n    const std::string secondCacheDate \u003d server.getCachedDateStr();\n\n    EXPECT_THAT(firstCacheDate, MatchesRegex(httpDateRegex));\n    EXPECT_THAT(secondCacheDate, MatchesRegex(httpDateRegex));\n    EXPECT_NE(firstCacheDate, secondCacheDate );\n\n```\n11 seconds so they are in different cache windows..? An 11 delay isn\u0027t great so this might take mocking the clock.. Feel free to ignore",
